Insurance Fraud Detection Using Machine Learning
📖 About the Project

Insurance fraud costs companies billions every year. In this project, I built a Machine Learning model to identify potentially fraudulent insurance claims based on historical claim data.

The goal is simple: detect suspicious claims early while minimizing false accusations. Because fraud cases are rare compared to legitimate claims, this project also focuses heavily on handling class imbalance and choosing the right evaluation metrics.

🎯 What This Project Covers

Exploratory Data Analysis (EDA) to understand claim patterns

Feature engineering to extract meaningful insights

Handling imbalanced data using techniques like SMOTE and class weighting

Training multiple classification models (Logistic Regression, Random Forest, XGBoost, etc.)

Evaluating performance using precision, recall, F1-score, and ROC-AUC

Interpreting predictions using SHAP for transparency

🛠️ Tech Stack

Python

Pandas & NumPy

Scikit-learn

XGBoost

Matplotlib & Seaborn

Imbalanced-learn

SHAP

📊 Dataset

The dataset includes:

Policy details

Claimant information

Claim amount

Incident details

A fraud label (Fraud / Not Fraud)

🚀 Workflow

Data cleaning and preprocessing

Exploratory data analysis

Feature engineering

Handling class imbalance

Model training and comparison

Performance evaluation

Model interpretation

🔎 Key Focus Areas

Improving fraud detection recall without increasing false positives excessively

Addressing real-world class imbalance

Making model predictions interpretable for business use

💡 Why This Matters

Fraud detection is not just a technical challenge — it’s a business-critical problem. A good model must balance accuracy, fairness, and explainability. This project reflects that balance.
